1. Top 20 companies with the largest valuations.¶

In [7]:
#Number of companies in the dataset
unicorn['Company'].nunique()
Out[7]:
935

There are 936 entries in the dateset but only 935 unique entries for 'Company'. Let's check if there are null values in this column.

In [8]:
unicorn['Company'].isnull().sum()
Out[8]:
0

There are no null values in the columns. Let's check for duplicate values.

In [9]:
unicorn[unicorn['Company'].duplicated()]
Out[9]:
Company Valuation ($B) Date Joined Country City Industry Investor 1 Investor 2 Investor 3 Investor 4
141 Bolt 4.75 2018-05-29 Estonia Tallinn Auto & transportation Didi Chuxing Diamler TMT Investments NaN

Company 'Bolt' is duplicated in the column. Let's retrieve the entries and see if all of their information in other columns are exactly the same

In [10]:
unicorn[unicorn['Company']=='Bolt']
Out[10]:
Company Valuation ($B) Date Joined Country City Industry Investor 1 Investor 2 Investor 3 Investor 4
94 Bolt 6.00 2021-10-08 United States San Francisco Fintech Activant Capital Tribe Capital General Atlantic NaN
141 Bolt 4.75 2018-05-29 Estonia Tallinn Auto & transportation Didi Chuxing Diamler TMT Investments NaN

The the information in the other columns are not the same. They come from different countries, United States and Estonia. Therefore we can keep them both in the dataset since they are two different companies that just have the same name.
